{
  "texts": [
    "This approach comprises several interesting special cases.",
    "For example, if preferences f (x i, x j) are derived from (one-dimensional) utilities u(x i) and u(x j), the kernel (9) effectively reduces to a two-dimensional kernel:",
    "Another interesting special case is the aggregation of single-criterion preference relations, such as valued concordance relations used in ELECTRE methods.",
    "Consider a single-criterion outranking relation (for the k th criterion) of the form",
    ", where p k and q k are threshold functions."
  ]
}